The conversion of `time_t` to string with a string parsing afterwards appears to me unnecessary complicated and error-prone. As already complained in [@Ted&#39;s comment](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/58151350/more-elegant-way-to-get-the-current-year-in-c#comment102686692_58151350), this may introduce localization of text output which may make the parsing non-robust.

Together with [`std::time()`](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/chrono/c/time), there are available

- [`std::localtime()`](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/chrono/c/localtime)
  &gt; Converts given time since epoch as std::time_t value into calendar time, expressed in local time.
- [`std::gmtime()`](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/chrono/c/gmtime)
  &gt; Converts given time since epoch as std::time_t value into calendar time, expressed in Coordinated Universal Time (UTC).

Both return a pointer to a [`struct tm`](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/chrono/c/tm) which contains among others a public member

&gt; `int tm_year` years since 1900

A small sample:
```cpp
#include &lt;ctime&gt;
#include &lt;iostream&gt;

int main()
{
  std::time_t t = std::time(nullptr);
  std::tm *const pTInfo = std::localtime(&amp;t);
  std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Current year: &quot; &lt;&lt; 1900 + pTInfo-&gt;tm_year &lt;&lt; &#39;\n&#39;;
}
```
